title: (3a) Intervals // 4x 8 mins (RI 4 mins)
description:
AEROBIC INTERVALS

AIM: Quality Intervals - aim is to accumulate a lot of work per session, rather than pushing power to the limit

TERRAIN: Intervals on a climb of ~5-6% - hill reps work well. If there are no hills, intervals can be performed into the win, or on the flat

FEELING GOOD: Perform 5x reps
FEELING TIRED: Reduce to 3 reps, and 1.25 hrs

- - - -

Seiler, S. JÃ¸ranson, K., Olesen, B.V. and Hetlelid, K.J. (2013). Adaptations to aerobic interval training: interactive effects of exercise intensity and total work duration. Scandinavian Journal of Medicine and Science in Sports. 23, 74-83.

"Accumulating 32 min of work at 90% HRmax induces greater adaptive gains than accumulating 16 min of work at 95% HRmax despite lower RPE"

- - - -

See the "Pre-activity comments" and "workout details" sections below for details of how to complete the session, target powers, coaching points, etc.
coachComments:
WARM UP
- Power zones: 51-61% FTP
- HR: <68%max // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 80-90 rpm

INTERVALS
- 4x 8 mins (RI 4 mins, see Coaching Points)
- Power zones: CUSTOM - see Workout Details
- HR: 85-90%max // RPE: 7-9 // Cadence: CUSTOM - see Workout Details
- Recovery: CUSTOM - see Workout Details

COOL DOWN
- Power zones: 51-61% FTP
- HR: <68%max // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 80-90 rpm

PHYSIOLOGICAL / PERFORMANCE ADAPTATIONS
++++ Plasma volume, stroke volume and cardiac output, VO2max
+++ Hypertrophy of slow-twitch muscle fibres, Muscle capillarisation
++ Muscle mitochondrial enzymes, lactate threshold, muscle glycogen storage, muscle fast-twitch fibre conversion (Type Iix to IIa)

- - - -

CUSTOM POWER AND CADENCE ZONES
- At PALMARES we believe in having as close to a bespoke training plan as possible - we employ CUSTOM zones throughout our plans dependent upon ability level, type and length of session, and training phase

COACHING POINTS
- Aim 1: Hit target power zone for intervals
- Aim 2: Option to add a rep, do not go harder
- Hold steady power for each Interval
- Recovery (RI) is 4 min, take longer if needed
- The goal is very consistent high-quality intervals

NUTRITION
- Consume carbohydrates pre-intervals
- Consider caffeine pre-intervals (if well-tolerated)
- Hydrate well throughout

title: (1b) Endurance
description:
ENDURANCE SESSION

AIM: Undulating paced endurance ride - designed to optimise training time.

TERRAIN: Flat to rolling roads (some climbs are ok) our on the indoor trainer.

FEELING GOOD: Extend up to 1.5 hrs
FEELING TIRED: Take the day off

- - - -

Coffey, V.G. and Hawley, J.A. (2007). The molecular basis of training adaptation. Sports Medicine. 37, 737-763.

Hood, D.A. (2009). Mechanisms of exercise-induced mitochondrial biogenesis in human skeletal muscle. Applied Physiology, Nutrition, and Metabolism. 34, 465-472.

- - - -

See the "Pre-activity comments" and "Workout details" sections below for details of how to complete the session, target powers, coaching points, etc.
coachComments:
WARM UP
- Power zones: 40-50% FTP
- HRmax: <65% // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 70-80 rpm

ENDURANCE
- Power zones: CUSTOM - see Workout Details
- HRmax: 65-80% // RPE: 4-5 (5 on climbs) // Cadence: CUSTOM - see Workout Details

COOL DOWN
- Power zones: 40-50% FTP
- HRmax: <65% // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 70-80 rpm

PHYSIOLOGICAL / PERFORMANCE ADAPTATIONS
++ Muscle mitochondrial enzymes, lactate threshold, muscle glycogen storage, muscle fast-twitch fibre conversion (Type IIx to IIa)
+ Plasma volume, hypertrophy of slow-twitch muscle fibres, muscle capillarisation, stroke volume / cardiac output, VO2max

- - - -

CUSTOM POWER AND CADENCE ZONES
- At PALMARES we believe in having as close to a bespoke training plan as possible - we employ CUSTOM zones throughout our plans dependent upon ability level, type and length of session, and training phase

COACHING POINTS
- Pacing discipline is very important during this session - stay in the power and HR zone throughout
- Aim for even power across session - It's ok to go slow uphill and into the wind
- Keep cadence brisk, change gear early

NUTRITION
- No on bike feeding required, but hydrate well

title: (1b) Endurance // 8x 10 sec sprints
description:
ENDURANCE + 10 sec sprints

AIM: Endurance trainingÂ with neuromuscular maximal power 10 sec sprints

TERRAIN: Flat to rolling roads. Perform sprints anywhere it's safe

FEELING GOOD: Extend to 2 hrs
FEELING TIRED: Reduce to 1 hr

- - - -

Almquist, N.M., Ettema, G, Hopker, J., Sandbank, Ã. and RÃ¸nnestad, B.R. (2019). The effect of 30-second sprints during prolonged exercise of gross efficiency, electromyography and pedalling technique in elite cyclists. International Journal of Sports Physiology and Performance. [Epub ahead of print]

"The inclusion of maximal repeated sprinting does not affect the gross economy changes [of the endurance training], and the ability to sprint is maintained throughout the entire session".

Gunnarsson, T.P., Brandt, N., Fiorenze, M., Hostrop, M., Pilegaard, H. and Bangsbo, J. (2019). Inclusion of sprints in moderate intensity continuous training leads to muscle oxidative adaptations in trained individuals. Physiological Reports. [Epub ahead of print]

"Addition of sprints... causes muscle oxidative adaptations in trained individuals" ... "time-trial performance" also improved.

- - - -

coachComments:
WARM UP
- Power zones: 48-58% FTP
- HRmax: <68% // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 80-90 rpm

ENDURANCE + 10x 10 sec Sprints
- Power zones: CUSTOM - see Workout Details
- HRmax: 68-78% // RPE: 3-4 (5 on climbs) // Cadence: CUSTOM - see Workout Details

COOL DOWN
- Power zones: 48-58% FTP
- HRmax: <68% // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 80-90 rpm

PHYSIOLOGICAL / PERFORMANCE ADAPTATIONS
+++ (Sprints) Neuromuscular power
++ (Endurance) Muscle mitochondrial enzymes, lactate threshold, muscle glycogen storage, muscle fast-twitch fibre conversion (Type IIx to IIa) // (Sprints) High-energy phosphate stores (ATP/PCr), hypertrophy of fast-twitch fibres
+ (Endurance) Plasma volume, hypertrophy of slow-twitch muscle fibres, muscle capillarisation, stroke volume / cardiac output, VO2max (Sprints) Anaerobic capacity

- - - -

CUSTOM POWER AND CADENCE ZONES
- At PALMARES we believe in having as close to a bespoke training plan as possible - we employ CUSTOM zones throughout our plans dependent upon ability level, type and length of session, and training phase

COACHING POINTS
- Pacing discipline is important during this session - stay in the power and HR zone during the ENDURANCE phase
- SPRINTS are FULL-GAS - aim to hit peak power within 10 secs

NUTRITION
- No on bike feeding required, but hydrate well

title: (3a) Endurance // Undulating Tempo
description:
ENDURANCE SESSION

AIM: Endurance training with change in tempo
TERRAIN: Flat to rolling roads

FEELING GOOD: Increase the power 5-10%
FEELING TIRED: Reduce the power 5-10%, and/or to 1.5 hrs

- - - -

WARM UP
- Power zones: 40-50% FTP
- HRmax: <68% // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 80-90 rpm

ENDURANCE
- Power zones: CUSTOM - see Workout Details
- HRmax: 68-78% // RPE: 3-4 (5 on climbs) // Cadence: CUSTOM - see Workout Details

COOL DOWN
- Power zones: 40-50% FTP
- HRmax: <68% // RPE: 2-3 // Cadence: 80-90 rpm

PHYSIOLOGICAL / PERFORMANCE ADAPTATIONS
++ Muscle mitochondrial enzymes, lactate threshold, muscle glycogen storage, muscle fast-twitch fibre conversion (Type IIx to IIa)
+ Plasma volume, hypertrophy of slow-twitch muscle fibres, muscle capillarisation, stroke volume / cardiac output, VO2max

- - - -

CUSTOM POWER AND CADENCE ZONES
- At PALMARES we believe in having as close to a bespoke training plan as possible - we employ CUSTOM zones throughout our plans dependent upon ability level, type and length of session, and training phase

COACHING POINTS
- Pacing discipline is very important during this session - stay in the power and HR zone from each phase of the undulations
- Aim for even power across each undulation - It's ok to go slow uphill and into the wind
- Keep cadence brisk, change gear early

NUTRITION
- Light on bike feeding
- Hydrate well, especially if it's hot
